# Agent attribution

## Rule
Every agent prints a **one-line banner** to chat before any other output, so the developer can see the four-layer chain (Command → Agent → Skill → Rule) play out live.

### Banner format

```
▸ <agent-name> — <short present-tense action, ≤ 8 words>
```

- Leading character is `▸` (single unicode triangle, low-token, scannable).
- Agent name matches the agent's file name without the `.md` (e.g., `ticket-completeness-agent`, `base-branch-picker-agent`).
- Action is what the agent is *about to do* in this turn, not a generic role description.
- One banner per phase. If an agent re-enters (e.g., after `revise`), it banners again with the new action.

### Gate banners
Approval gates also banner — they are pipeline checkpoints the developer interacts with:

```
▸ Gate 1 — waiting for your approval (plan + per-repo base branches)
▸ Gate 2 — waiting for your approval (review the consolidated JIRA comment first)
```

### Parallel reviewers
The 14 review agents run in parallel under one orchestrator banner — not 14 separate banners (would be noisy and costly). Use:

```
▸ review-agents (×14, parallel) — analysing the committed diff
```

When all 14 return, the orchestrator emits one more banner before posting to JIRA:

```
▸ review-aggregator — posting consolidated findings to JIRA-<KEY>
```

### Halts and failures
When an agent halts the pipeline, the banner names the agent that halted:

```
▸ ticket-completeness-agent — HALT: missing acceptance criteria, ticket unassigned
```

## Why
Without attribution, the developer sees disembodied PASS/FAIL/HALT output and has no idea which agent ran or which to debug. Naming the agent makes the four-layer chain visible, which is exactly what the workflow's design intent (`getting-started.md` §3.5) promises. The cost is tiny — about 5 tokens per banner — and the readability gain is substantial.

## Constraints
- **One banner per phase, not per sub-step.** Don't banner every file read or every tool call inside an agent's turn.
- **No emoji.** Keep it terminal-clean and low-token.
- **No status colours / markdown headers / horizontal rules.** Just the single triangle prefix line.
- **Action line is not the agent's full role.** "checking AC, assignee, repro steps" — not "Enforces the ticket-completeness rule for every JIRA-touching command."
- **Reviewers MUST use the single grouped banner.** Even if some finish earlier than others, the orchestrator suppresses per-reviewer banners.
- **Do not banner for read-only sub-agents inside another agent's turn** (e.g., a skill called by an agent does not banner — only the agent does).

## Examples

### Good
```
▸ jira-agent — fetching EFP-1423 from JIRA
... intake JSON ...
▸ ticket-completeness-agent — checking AC, assignee, repro steps
... PASS / FAIL table ...
▸ router-agent — resolving building-block → owning services
... routing JSON ...
▸ planner-agent — drafting cross-repo plan
... plan ...
▸ Gate 1 — waiting for your approval (plan + per-repo base branches)
```

### Bad
```
✅ Jira fetched
🔍 Now checking completeness...
[ROUTER] Routing...
**Planner Output:**
...
```
(emoji noise, inconsistent prefixes, no consistent naming)

```
▸ jira-agent — starting
▸ jira-agent — calling API
▸ jira-agent — parsing response
▸ jira-agent — writing intake
```
(banner per sub-step instead of one per phase)

